  "text": "Among the three pairs of anti-gp41 MAbs tested, two displayed antagonism in the neutralization of HIV-1 89.6 . Thus, when MAb 98.6 (which does not neutralize HIV-1 89.6 ) was used in combination with MAb 2F5 (Fig. 4m) or with MAb 50-69 ( Fig. 4n) (both of which neutralize HIV-1 89.6 [ Fig. 2] ), the potency of neutralization was reduced. This is the first time that antagonism has been shown between two anti-gp41 MAbs, although a similar antagonistic effect in HIV-1 neutralization has been previously reported with a pair of anti-gp120 MAbs directed against gp120 (with Abs to gp120 V3 and anti-gp120 CD4bd [CITATION_1] ). Antagonism between Abs has also been demonstrated in other virus systems [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Several explanations could explain this phenomenon of antagonism: negative cooperativity between two MAbs could reflect conformational rearrangements induced by one of the Abs, inhibiting subsequent interactions with the neutralizing Ab of the pair. Abs might also interfere with each other's binding by steric hindrance [CITATION_4] ; the antagonism between MAbs 98-6 and 2F5 might be an example of this. Thus, Gorny and Zolla-Pazner (36) recently showed that MAbs 98-6 and 2F5 could bind to peptides and peptide complexes representing the prefusogenic and fusogenic forms of gp41. In that study, 98-6 had a higher affinity for the peptide complexes representing the fusogenic form, than did 2F5. Thus, the binding of 98-6, which fails to neutralize HIV-1 89.6 , could interfere with the binding of 2F5, leading to the antagonism noted (Fig.  4m) . In contrast, MAbs 50-69 and 2F5 recognize distinct epitopes in gp41 and display independent (additive) reactivity against HIV-1 89.6.",
